18
00:01:13.160 --> 00:01:14.300
These are my disclosures.

19
00:01:16.400 --> 00:01:19.900
All right. So when we think about fibroblasts, this is one of the most

20
00:01:19.960 --> 00:01:23.700
fundamental cell types. It's part of

21
00:01:24.260 --> 00:01:27.780
every normal healthy tissue. These are the cells that are

22
00:01:28.780 --> 00:01:32.220
making your connective tissue, performing lots of structural

23
00:01:32.230 --> 00:01:35.980
functions, and although this

24
00:01:36.000 --> 00:01:39.780
session is about fibroblasts and cancer, I do want to iterate that these

25
00:01:39.880 --> 00:01:43.340
are normal cells that are very important for homeostasis.

26
00:01:44.360 --> 00:01:47.920
And they're not just one kind. And so if you look in various

27
00:01:48.000 --> 00:01:51.600
tissues, the fibroblasts are poised for separate

28
00:01:51.700 --> 00:01:55.640
functions in those tissues. All of them make extracellular matrix, some more

29
00:01:55.660 --> 00:01:59.200
than others. But they also have a lot of metabolic functions.

30
00:01:59.880 --> 00:02:01.960
They can secrete a lot of proteins.

31
00:02:02.020 --> 00:02:06.000
These are cells that are really good at protein biosynthesis that's important

32
00:02:06.020 --> 00:02:09.521
for making extracellular matrix, for remodeling extracellular matrix.

33
00:02:09.880 --> 00:02:13.860
But they can also do things like secrete growth factors and cytokines

34
00:02:14.180 --> 00:02:17.860
that can call in immune cells as needed or restrain them as needed.

35
00:02:19.180 --> 00:02:22.780
And so this is a picture form, but it actually comes from a

36
00:02:22.920 --> 00:02:25.540
lot of transcriptional profiling.

37
00:02:25.800 --> 00:02:29.780
This is a really nice study from Shannon Turley's group, where

38
00:02:29.890 --> 00:02:33.520
they looked at healthy tissues, and you can see the

39
00:02:33.560 --> 00:02:37.360
tissues here. And a lot of them were public data sets where

40
00:02:37.400 --> 00:02:41.160
they subsetted out fibroblasts and just asked, "What does the fibroblasts look like

41
00:02:41.220 --> 00:02:43.890
in lung, in bone, in intestine?" And

42
00:02:45.320 --> 00:02:48.380
they're slightly different. And so you see that there's some

43
00:02:48.420 --> 00:02:52.020
heterogeneity. They're all capable of making extracellular

44
00:02:52.080 --> 00:02:56.060
matrix, but they have slightly different gene transcriptions that make

45
00:02:56.320 --> 00:02:58.780
the normal functions that are needed in those tissues.

46
00:03:01.760 --> 00:03:05.180
A huge function, of course, is to produce the extracellular matrix.

47
00:03:05.360 --> 00:03:09.109
We think of this in terms of collagens, but there's also a lot of

48
00:03:09.120 --> 00:03:13.040
proteoglycans in there. Huge amount of ECM

49
00:03:13.080 --> 00:03:16.670
components. This is an incredibly diverse set of

50
00:03:16.700 --> 00:03:20.590
proteins that can be cross-linked in long fibers, that

51
00:03:20.620 --> 00:03:21.549
can be cross-linked

52
00:03:22.920 --> 00:03:26.460
in a more chaotic way. And a lot of the

53
00:03:26.500 --> 00:03:30.260
remodeling of the extracellular matrix is also performed by fibroblasts.

54
00:03:30.480 --> 00:03:32.040
Macrophages can contribute, too.

55
00:03:32.500 --> 00:03:36.360
But in terms of both building and breaking down collagen, making

56
00:03:36.400 --> 00:03:39.820
matrix metalloproteases to make sure that the

57
00:03:41.140 --> 00:03:43.640
extracellular matrix is appropriately remodeled.

58
00:03:44.540 --> 00:03:48.240
This is a cartoon, but also some really nice work.

59
00:03:48.840 --> 00:03:52.180
This study was led by Richard Hynes' lab,

60
00:03:52.700 --> 00:03:56.440
asking what proteins are there? And I think proteomics has

61
00:03:56.480 --> 00:04:00.400
really led the way in this, where you can take the extracellular matrix from a

62
00:04:00.460 --> 00:04:04.350
tissue, you can decellularize it, and ask, "Well, what is left?"

63
00:04:04.900 --> 00:04:08.260
And it's a surprisingly rich set of proteins,

64
00:04:09.140 --> 00:04:12.480
some of which are the core matrisome that are

65
00:04:12.520 --> 00:04:16.221
detected across

66
00:04:16.300 --> 00:04:19.740
tissues, but some of them are also more tissue-dependent.

67
00:04:20.640 --> 00:04:24.480
And asking what does a tissue need in its extracellular matrix can be very

68
00:04:24.540 --> 00:04:28.380
revealing about the function of the fibroblasts that secreted it in the first

69
00:04:28.440 --> 00:04:30.800
place, and that tissue in particular.

70
00:04:33.600 --> 00:04:37.560
And so we talked a bit about healthy homeostasis, but of

71
00:04:37.600 --> 00:04:39.830
course, tissues can become inflamed.

72
00:04:40.340 --> 00:04:44.310
And one of the huge important roles of the fibroblasts is

73
00:04:44.360 --> 00:04:47.740
to sense tissue damage and to help mediate the

74
00:04:47.780 --> 00:04:50.740
wound healing and remodeling of the extracellular matrix.

75
00:04:51.360 --> 00:04:51.660
And

76
00:04:53.120 --> 00:04:56.860
so the same subset of fibroblasts that we just surveyed

77
00:04:56.880 --> 00:05:00.740
across healthy tissues also has a counterpart

78
00:05:00.800 --> 00:05:02.120
in diseased tissues

79
00:05:02.920 --> 00:05:06.480
that look slightly different, but are oftentimes recruiting

80
00:05:06.580 --> 00:05:10.420
in innate inflammatory cells, so they make a lot of chemokines.

81
00:05:10.500 --> 00:05:13.730
These are your CCL and CXCL family of proteins,

82
00:05:14.620 --> 00:05:18.080
which form gradients that are deposited in the

83
00:05:18.160 --> 00:05:22.140
extracellular matrix that allow for things like monocytes and neutrophils

84
00:05:22.180 --> 00:05:22.840
to come in.

85
00:05:23.820 --> 00:05:27.400
Monocytes, of course, can differentiate into macrophages and help

86
00:05:28.120 --> 00:05:30.560
with that wound repair and tissue healing.

87
00:05:31.740 --> 00:05:32.260
All right.

88
00:05:34.560 --> 00:05:38.520
And this is going on in cancer. It's going on

89
00:05:39.100 --> 00:05:42.850
at a much higher rate. And so cancer was

90
00:05:43.280 --> 00:05:45.760
originally described as a wound that doesn't heal.

91
00:05:46.340 --> 00:05:50.330
And so many of these activation of fibroblast pathways, of

92
00:05:50.420 --> 00:05:53.280
course, are also happening in cancer. They're happening chronically.

93
00:05:53.300 --> 00:05:54.580
They're happening for a long time.

94
00:05:55.100 --> 00:05:58.930
And many of the processes that we think about in terms of cancer directly

95
00:05:59.020 --> 00:06:02.570
act to activate fibroblasts. And so certainly, these are

96
00:06:02.800 --> 00:06:06.656
contact-dependent signalsWith the

97
00:06:06.716 --> 00:06:08.456
cancer cells and extracellular matrix,

98
00:06:09.496 --> 00:06:13.396
DNA damage, factors like TGF-beta, which we're going to talk a lot

99
00:06:13.456 --> 00:06:17.216
more about, and stress induced by hypoxia or

100
00:06:17.236 --> 00:06:20.976
reactive oxygen species, can certainly all activate these sort

101
00:06:21.036 --> 00:06:24.816
of constitutive fibroblasts that are present in whatever tissue the

102
00:06:24.856 --> 00:06:28.216
cancer is arising in and turn them into this so-called CAF.

103
00:06:28.316 --> 00:06:30.336
This cancer-associated fibroblasts.

104
00:06:30.736 --> 00:06:33.956
And so we've appreciated these for a long time, that they're in all

105
00:06:34.076 --> 00:06:37.976
cancers. They seem to be really bad or at

106
00:06:38.016 --> 00:06:41.716
least complicated and sort of appreciating that they

107
00:06:41.796 --> 00:06:44.796
have an origin with the normal tissue

108
00:06:45.496 --> 00:06:46.516
is an important

109
00:06:48.036 --> 00:06:48.736
point to note.

110
00:06:49.916 --> 00:06:53.756
And so although we have CAFs in every cancer type,

111
00:06:54.656 --> 00:06:58.276
we are today going to use as an example pancreatic

112
00:06:58.336 --> 00:07:01.996
cancer. And so our speakers today all are sort of

113
00:07:02.096 --> 00:07:03.796
active in the pancreatic cancer field.

114
00:07:04.236 --> 00:07:07.405
And the reason that pancreatic cancer has kind of led the way in thinking about

115
00:07:07.405 --> 00:07:10.516
fibroblasts is because it is highly desmoplastic.

116
00:07:10.856 --> 00:07:14.836
I have a cartoon that I drew here, but you can also see from the H&amp;E

117
00:07:14.876 --> 00:07:18.056
that you have these tiny nests of cancer cells that are the dark

118
00:07:18.156 --> 00:07:19.116
purple,

119
00:07:19.936 --> 00:07:23.756
that are kind of in this giant sea of extracellular matrix.

120
00:07:23.916 --> 00:07:27.196
And so you have these activated fibroblasts making this huge amount of

121
00:07:27.256 --> 00:07:29.156
stroma that can,

122
00:07:29.976 --> 00:07:33.816
by its sheer biomass, outweigh the actual cancer cells themselves.

123
00:07:34.476 --> 00:07:37.376
And so this has been appreciated for a very long time.

124
00:07:38.916 --> 00:07:39.756
And so

125
00:07:40.876 --> 00:07:41.736
how can we

126
00:07:43.296 --> 00:07:47.116
therapeutically intervene? And I would say that we're going to talk

127
00:07:47.196 --> 00:07:50.256
about all of these strategies to either deplete

128
00:07:50.276 --> 00:07:53.876
fibroblasts or the extracellular matrix, and this kind of makes sense.

129
00:07:53.936 --> 00:07:57.126
You look at something like pancreatic cancer, it has a very horrible prognosis.

130
00:07:57.176 --> 00:08:00.476
It's got all of this desmoplasia. And so the obvious

131
00:08:00.936 --> 00:08:04.496
thought is, okay, well, maybe that stroma is

132
00:08:05.096 --> 00:08:09.076
contributing to progression of the tumor, and so what can we do about it?

133
00:08:10.076 --> 00:08:12.396
And so these are strategies that have been tried.

134
00:08:13.356 --> 00:08:15.136
We'll talk about Smoothened inhibitors,

135
00:08:17.355 --> 00:08:21.116
pegylated hyaluronidase to enzymatically digest the extracellular

136
00:08:21.176 --> 00:08:21.696
matrix,

137
00:08:22.856 --> 00:08:25.756
blockade of two different cytokines, and CAR T cells.

138
00:08:27.776 --> 00:08:30.396
All right. And so what is Smoothened?

139
00:08:30.596 --> 00:08:34.496
This is a cartoon from Sunil Hingorani's lab, who's worked on this

140
00:08:34.536 --> 00:08:38.376
quite a bit, where the tumor cells themselves can

141
00:08:38.437 --> 00:08:41.596
make these Hedgehog ligands that will bind to

142
00:08:41.636 --> 00:08:45.516
Patched1, which is a natural inhibitor of the Smoothened

143
00:08:45.656 --> 00:08:47.236
protein, which can then

144
00:08:48.496 --> 00:08:52.276
prevent it from signaling. And if you block this pathway, then Smoothened will

145
00:08:52.316 --> 00:08:56.176
naturally activate these Gli transcription factors, and this can lead

146
00:08:56.256 --> 00:08:59.856
to proliferation and activation of these fibroblasts.

147
00:09:01.576 --> 00:09:05.276
And so there was a seminal study published a while ago now by Ken

148
00:09:05.356 --> 00:09:05.916
Olive's group,

149
00:09:06.736 --> 00:09:10.136
when he was in Tev Tuveson's lab, looking at, okay, well, maybe

150
00:09:10.756 --> 00:09:14.236
can we use these Smoothened inhibitors to try to kind of

151
00:09:15.036 --> 00:09:17.876
debulk this extracellular matrix with the

152
00:09:17.976 --> 00:09:21.925
observation, as you can see in these pictures, that if you have

153
00:09:21.956 --> 00:09:25.716
a pancreatic tumor growing in a spontaneous so-called

154
00:09:25.776 --> 00:09:26.896
KPC gem mouse,

155
00:09:27.696 --> 00:09:30.316
it's this dark spot in the middle. And what is this dark spot?

156
00:09:30.376 --> 00:09:33.996
Well, this is looking at sort of a fluorescent gemcitabine

157
00:09:34.116 --> 00:09:37.916
trying to get in, and you can see that the drug is able to get everywhere in the

158
00:09:37.956 --> 00:09:39.656
pancreas but not the tumor. Right?

159
00:09:39.736 --> 00:09:42.156
And so it was sort of obvious, like okay, it's very dense.

160
00:09:42.236 --> 00:09:44.296
You try to cut into this, it's very hard, like a rock.

161
00:09:44.796 --> 00:09:48.786
Maybe if we got rid of that extracellular matrix by sort of inhibiting these

162
00:09:48.816 --> 00:09:50.936
fibroblasts, could we get more drug in?

163
00:09:51.736 --> 00:09:53.716
And so gemcitabine is one of the

164
00:09:54.696 --> 00:09:58.346
chemotherapies used in pancreas cancer, and you can see in the mouse model that

165
00:09:58.376 --> 00:10:02.256
combination of the Smoothened inhibitor with gemcitabine is able to extend

166
00:10:02.296 --> 00:10:05.516
survival in an incredibly difficult mouse model.

167
00:10:08.956 --> 00:10:12.676
So this had some unfortunate results in humans,

168
00:10:12.736 --> 00:10:16.136
though. And I do want to kind of show you the mouse and the human

169
00:10:16.396 --> 00:10:20.026
data. And so the initial trial that was

170
00:10:20.116 --> 00:10:24.066
started right on the heels of this pre-clinical study was using

171
00:10:24.096 --> 00:10:25.156
a Smoothened inhibitor,

172
00:10:26.016 --> 00:10:29.856
that's listed here, where the trial had to stop

173
00:10:29.916 --> 00:10:33.696
early. This was not actually published, but it was released by the company,

174
00:10:34.156 --> 00:10:38.116
that the Smoothened inhibitor plus gemcitabine actually made the tumors progress

175
00:10:38.396 --> 00:10:40.576
faster than with chemotherapy alone.

176
00:10:41.336 --> 00:10:45.236
A second trial was done where you can see that there was not really

177
00:10:45.276 --> 00:10:48.256
much of a difference, but I think that this early press release

178
00:10:48.776 --> 00:10:51.946
really was a huge wake-up call to the field saying,

179
00:10:52.536 --> 00:10:56.296
"Wow, we really don't understand fibroblasts." We show that we

180
00:10:56.336 --> 00:11:00.316
can deplete them or sort of quiesce them, and this idea that

181
00:11:00.336 --> 00:11:01.436
we just get more drug in

182
00:11:02.476 --> 00:11:06.216
ended up making the patient's survival worse.

183
00:11:08.776 --> 00:11:12.496
Similarly, there have been strategies to try to deplete the extracellular

184
00:11:12.556 --> 00:11:16.516
matrix, and so pegylated hyaluronidase, this is an enzyme that kind

185
00:11:16.556 --> 00:11:20.176
of cleaves up hyaluronic acid, sort of pictured here in

186
00:11:20.236 --> 00:11:21.476
yellow. And

187
00:11:22.396 --> 00:11:26.236
if you look by immunohistochemistry, you can see that there's a range

188
00:11:26.336 --> 00:11:30.216
of hyaluronic acid in pancreatic cancer in humans, some of which

189
00:11:30.256 --> 00:11:34.216
can be quite, quite high. And so if you are able

190
00:11:34.256 --> 00:11:38.066
to digest this enzymatically, then maybe you'll sort of dedensify that

191
00:11:38.096 --> 00:11:41.976
extracellular matrix. The blood vessels are going to be less

192
00:11:41.996 --> 00:11:45.276
compressed, and you'll be able to get more drug in.

193
00:11:46.556 --> 00:11:50.396
And so the initial Phase II trial with gemcitabine and

194
00:11:50.436 --> 00:11:54.336
paclitaxel, listed here as AG, was

195
00:11:54.396 --> 00:11:58.285
promising. Although in Phase III, you can see that there was really

196
00:11:58.336 --> 00:12:01.916
no effect of using the pegylated hyaluronidase to

197
00:12:02.616 --> 00:12:05.116
increase chemotherapy delivery to the tumor.

198
00:12:05.916 --> 00:12:06.276
And

199
00:12:07.156 --> 00:12:10.476
very strikingly, if you just change the chemotherapy

200
00:12:10.576 --> 00:12:13.968
regimenAnd this is now FOLFIRINOX,

201
00:12:14.428 --> 00:12:15.228
which is

202
00:12:16.368 --> 00:12:19.428
used very frequently in first-line pancreas cancer.

203
00:12:19.628 --> 00:12:22.488
You can see that these labels are not mixed up, that in fact,

204
00:12:23.648 --> 00:12:26.308
depleting the extracellular matrix with pegylated

205
00:12:26.348 --> 00:12:30.248
hyaluronidase worsens overall survival.

206
00:12:31.168 --> 00:12:31.648
And so

207
00:12:32.808 --> 00:12:36.448
this again sort of had a moment of reckoning for the

208
00:12:36.528 --> 00:12:39.848
field where we thought, well, maybe there's something about this, that

209
00:12:39.868 --> 00:12:42.318
there's fibroblast heterogeneity.

210
00:12:43.368 --> 00:12:46.648
Are there some fibroblasts that are actually good, that are sort of tumor

211
00:12:46.668 --> 00:12:49.638
restraining, and maybe we need to understand this better.

212
00:12:50.928 --> 00:12:51.248
And so

213
00:12:52.428 --> 00:12:55.948
this led to some initial discoveries on sort of bucketing

214
00:12:55.988 --> 00:12:59.588
fibroblasts into multiple subsets.

215
00:12:59.668 --> 00:13:03.548
And one of the first ways of thinking about this was looking

216
00:13:03.588 --> 00:13:07.448
at transcriptional profiling. And you could see, this is work

217
00:13:07.768 --> 00:13:11.728
from Julia Biffi when she was with Dave Tuveson, that the

218
00:13:11.868 --> 00:13:15.867
fibroblasts that are next to the cancer cells, that are sort of surrounding

219
00:13:15.888 --> 00:13:19.088
these little cancer cell nests, receive a lot of

220
00:13:19.128 --> 00:13:22.228
TGF-beta signaling, and they become these sort of

221
00:13:22.308 --> 00:13:25.648
myofibroblastic-like CAFs or myCAFs.

222
00:13:26.168 --> 00:13:28.248
These make a lot of extracellular matrix.

223
00:13:28.308 --> 00:13:30.868
They have direct contact with the tumor cells.

224
00:13:32.148 --> 00:13:35.668
Whereas the fibroblasts that are sort of further away

225
00:13:36.468 --> 00:13:40.388
are not getting as much TGF-beta signaling, and they can

226
00:13:40.468 --> 00:13:44.388
see more sort of IL-1, as it induces this phenotype.

227
00:13:44.868 --> 00:13:48.158
And they're making some extracellular matrix, but a lot of

228
00:13:48.388 --> 00:13:51.728
cytokines and chemokines that are interacting with the immune system.

229
00:13:51.788 --> 00:13:55.708
So IL-6 is hugely produced by these fibroblasts,

230
00:13:56.688 --> 00:14:00.068
as is the Th2 alarmin IL-33, as well as

231
00:14:00.468 --> 00:14:04.048
complement proteins. And so these were termed inflammatory

232
00:14:04.088 --> 00:14:08.028
fibroblasts or iCAFs, thinking there would be an interface

233
00:14:08.068 --> 00:14:11.608
with the immune system. And when we said, "Oh, okay, look, there are two kinds of

234
00:14:11.648 --> 00:14:14.008
fibroblasts. Maybe there's the good kind and the bad kind."

235
00:14:15.388 --> 00:14:17.568
And so this has now been tried in humans.

236
00:14:17.648 --> 00:14:21.628
Okay, we know that there are cytokine signals that prevent or

237
00:14:22.008 --> 00:14:23.128
preclude development

238
00:14:24.388 --> 00:14:27.668
of these sort of iCAFs and myCAFs. And so I'm going to show you data

239
00:14:27.868 --> 00:14:31.408
from a blockade of TGF-beta, which should

240
00:14:31.628 --> 00:14:35.248
deplete the myCAFs, not the iCAFs, and IL-1 beta

241
00:14:35.328 --> 00:14:37.548
blockade, which should have the converse effect.

242
00:14:39.128 --> 00:14:42.668
And so this is the mouse data. This was done in my lab, where we looked at

243
00:14:42.708 --> 00:14:46.548
TGF-beta blockade in a mouse model of pancreas cancer, showing that it

244
00:14:46.608 --> 00:14:50.468
nicely prevents signaling through phospho-SMAD2.

245
00:14:50.938 --> 00:14:54.048
And if you look at fibroblasts, you can see that indeed, the sort of

