pancreas tumor, it's not so desmoplastic.

493
00:29:07.276 --> 00:29:10.996
So the different type of cancer drive different responses in the same

494
00:29:11.056 --> 00:29:11.656
fibroblast.

495
00:29:12.496 --> 00:29:13.596
Have you

496
00:29:14.716 --> 00:29:18.116
done something like that, seeing which signals are given by one cell to

497
00:29:18.156 --> 00:29:21.936
respect to another, and not treating the fibroblast as a unique

498
00:29:22.096 --> 00:29:23.636
species that respond always the same?

499
00:29:24.516 --> 00:29:28.236
Yes, that is a great question. I'm glad you bring up pancreatic neuroendocrine

500
00:29:28.276 --> 00:29:31.886
tumors, because again, it tells you same organ, very, very different histology,

501
00:29:32.056 --> 00:29:34.676
very different results in sort of activation of fibroblasts.

502
00:29:34.716 --> 00:29:38.036
And so certainly there is crosstalk even with the

503
00:29:38.116 --> 00:29:42.066
neoplastic cells as well. And so a lot of really good work done, I'd say senescent

504
00:29:42.066 --> 00:29:45.996
cancer cells and sort of how they produce a lot of cytokines that could activate

505
00:29:46.016 --> 00:29:48.676
fibroblasts and give you more of the sort of iCAF phenotype.

506
00:29:49.476 --> 00:29:53.136
And the neuroendocrine tumors also make a lot of different factors.

507
00:29:53.756 --> 00:29:57.556
I don't know if my panel wants to contribute more towards PNETs.

508
00:29:58.416 --> 00:30:02.096
But you see this giant inflammatory reaction, and

509
00:30:02.156 --> 00:30:03.976
yet, the tumor's progressing, right?

510
00:30:04.096 --> 00:30:08.076
So not all inflammation is good. Just like not all fibroblasts

511
00:30:08.096 --> 00:30:10.436
are good, but they could certainly act very differently.

512
00:30:11.196 --> 00:30:11.456
Thank you.

513
00:30:11.816 --> 00:30:12.116
Okay.

514
00:30:13.696 --> 00:30:15.636
All right. Maybe last question. Yeah.

515
00:30:15.696 --> 00:30:15.936
Thanks.

516
00:30:17.080 --> 00:30:20.860
I have a question. Since you say that depletion might not be the right way to go,

517
00:30:20.900 --> 00:30:24.600
what do you think about reprogramming and programming, let's say, from yeah

518
00:30:24.920 --> 00:30:27.680
protumoral to anti-tumor fibroblasts?

519
00:30:29.160 --> 00:30:32.260
Yes. So I think this is a very active area of research.

520
00:30:32.320 --> 00:30:36.000
Can we reprogram a fibroblast? We know they're very plastic, so is there some

521
00:30:36.060 --> 00:30:40.000
kind of signal we can give therapeutically that will keep them in whatever

522
00:30:40.060 --> 00:30:40.860
the good state is?

523
00:30:41.680 --> 00:30:42.600
I think we

524
00:30:43.700 --> 00:30:46.130
want to be really sure we know what that good state is,

525
00:30:47.220 --> 00:30:50.929
first, and how well or how

526
00:30:50.960 --> 00:30:52.850
permanent that reprogramming is.

527
00:30:52.960 --> 00:30:56.620
I think you're also stuck with, as soon as you stop using the drug, you can get it

528
00:30:56.660 --> 00:30:58.240
to revert. So,

529
00:30:59.360 --> 00:31:03.230
similar ideas have been proposed for macrophage reprogramming as well, and I

530
00:31:03.240 --> 00:31:07.150
think it goes down a slippery slope of, is this

531
00:31:07.180 --> 00:31:10.060
really the effect you want, and how long can you sustain that?

532
00:31:10.140 --> 00:31:13.540
So I think there's a role for this fibroblast

533
00:31:13.600 --> 00:31:17.350
reprogramming, but I think it's in combination with

534
00:31:17.380 --> 00:31:21.280
other therapies that are either directly killing tumor cells or inducing an

535
00:31:21.319 --> 00:31:25.160
immune response that can make that sort of transient

536
00:31:25.220 --> 00:31:27.540
nature of the fibroblast reprogramming permanent.

537
00:31:28.180 --> 00:31:28.420
Thanks.

538
00:31:28.860 --> 00:31:29.060
Yeah.

539
00:31:30.080 --> 00:31:30.420
Okay.

540
00:31:31.280 --> 00:31:32.059
Thank you.

541
00:31:35.680 --> 00:31:36.110
I will

542
00:31:37.840 --> 00:31:39.860
introduce my colleague, Mara Sherman.

543
00:31:42.840 --> 00:31:46.480
All right. Well, thank you, chair extraordinaire, Stephanie, for the opportunity to

544
00:31:46.520 --> 00:31:49.160
participate in this session and for starting us off so nicely.

545
00:31:50.160 --> 00:31:53.630
So my lab studies cellular hierarchies in the tumor microenvironment,

546
00:31:54.140 --> 00:31:57.720
and our goal really is to understand how this immune-suppressive, chemo-resistant

547
00:31:57.740 --> 00:32:01.140
microenvironment gets established, but also how it might be

548
00:32:01.180 --> 00:32:03.280
dismantled for therapeutic benefit.

549
00:32:04.500 --> 00:32:05.300
No disclosures.

550
00:32:06.280 --> 00:32:10.080
So in this vein, we spend a lot of time thinking about mesenchymal elements such as

551
00:32:10.180 --> 00:32:14.160
fibroblasts. And really our motivation is evidence from context

552
00:32:14.220 --> 00:32:17.500
of development, health, and inflammation that

553
00:32:17.540 --> 00:32:21.110
fibroblasts provide critical instructive cues that

554
00:32:21.140 --> 00:32:23.950
regulate epithelial cell state and tissue function.

555
00:32:24.740 --> 00:32:28.280
So for example, in the embryo, the splanchnic mesenchyme

556
00:32:28.440 --> 00:32:32.349
critically instructs alveolar airway epithelium formation

557
00:32:32.380 --> 00:32:36.120
in the developing lung, and that epithelial mesenchymal crosstalk

558
00:32:36.160 --> 00:32:38.720
remains critical for lung function in early life.

559
00:32:39.320 --> 00:32:42.700
In healthy adult tissue, there are positionally defined

560
00:32:42.800 --> 00:32:46.360
populations of fibroblasts that secrete distinct developmental

561
00:32:46.430 --> 00:32:50.340
cues that program epithelial heterogeneity in a way that's critical for

562
00:32:50.400 --> 00:32:54.260
tissue function, and this is really nicely exemplified along the length of the

563
00:32:54.300 --> 00:32:55.340
intestinal crypt.

564
00:32:56.280 --> 00:32:59.840
And in the context of inflammation, there's a beautiful recent example from the

565
00:32:59.900 --> 00:33:03.800
mighty reindeer showing that anatomically distinct populations

566
00:33:03.860 --> 00:33:07.090
of fibroblasts can respond to similar wounding

567
00:33:07.200 --> 00:33:11.040
insults with totally different secretomes, and therefore

568
00:33:11.080 --> 00:33:13.420
different impacts on the epithelial compartment.

569
00:33:13.470 --> 00:33:17.320
So specifically, a wounding insult to a regenerative organ, in this

570
00:33:17.400 --> 00:33:21.360
case, specifically the velvet or the antlers, causes those fibroblasts

571
00:33:21.400 --> 00:33:24.960
to secrete regenerative factors, stem cell niche

572
00:33:25.140 --> 00:33:28.780
cues that ultimately promote epithelial cell proliferation,

573
00:33:28.860 --> 00:33:30.820
regeneration, and tissue repair.

574
00:33:31.780 --> 00:33:35.080
Whereas a really comparable wounding insult on the back skin

575
00:33:35.440 --> 00:33:39.080
causes fibroblasts really to enter an inflammatory state and

576
00:33:39.160 --> 00:33:42.230
ultimately result in epithelial cell death and a scarring

577
00:33:42.260 --> 00:33:46.240
reaction. And importantly, really comparable fibroblast transcriptional

578
00:33:46.300 --> 00:33:49.700
states are found in human skin in the fetus versus the

579
00:33:49.900 --> 00:33:53.500
adult. And so, of course, we know that there are these

580
00:33:53.540 --> 00:33:57.440
intrinsic differences among these positionally or anatomically

581
00:33:57.500 --> 00:34:01.380
defined fibroblast populations, and we're motivated to understand how

582
00:34:01.460 --> 00:34:04.700
about this epithelial mesenchymal crosstalk and fibroblast

583
00:34:04.710 --> 00:34:07.040
heterogeneity in the context of cancer.

584
00:34:09.060 --> 00:34:09.460
So there

585
00:34:10.281 --> 00:34:14.230
has long been evidence that fibroblasts can really have heterogeneous

586
00:34:14.380 --> 00:34:17.281
functional impacts on cancer cell growth.

587
00:34:17.900 --> 00:34:21.140
Almost 60 years ago now, Michael Stoker's lab

588
00:34:21.180 --> 00:34:24.861
demonstrated that normal static fibroblasts could suppress the

589
00:34:24.980 --> 00:34:26.900
growth of polyoma transformed cells.

590
00:34:26.920 --> 00:34:30.700
This was really an early example that components of normal tissue

591
00:34:30.740 --> 00:34:34.500
architecture could serve as barriers to tumor genesis.

592
00:34:34.540 --> 00:34:38.460
About 20 years later, pioneering work from Mina Bissell's lab in the chick

593
00:34:38.540 --> 00:34:42.500
embryo comparing tumor progression in an uninjured versus

594
00:34:42.540 --> 00:34:45.830
a clipped or wounded chick wing showed that a local

595
00:34:46.000 --> 00:34:49.620
fibroinflammatory or wounding reaction was permissive to Rous

596
00:34:49.660 --> 00:34:51.880
sarcoma virus-mediated tumor formation.

597
00:34:51.920 --> 00:34:55.700
This was really a seminal example of a principle that's been shown many

598
00:34:55.761 --> 00:34:59.330
times since, that a fibroinflammatory microenvironment can

599
00:34:59.380 --> 00:35:01.260
promote tumor genesis.

600
00:35:02.900 --> 00:35:06.540
So we study these networks in the context of pancreatic cancer really because, as

601
00:35:06.620 --> 00:35:10.200
Stephanie so nicely described, these really are the

602
00:35:10.240 --> 00:35:12.820
poster child of a fibroinflammatory malignancy.

603
00:35:13.380 --> 00:35:17.340
So pancreatic cancer certainly exhibits heterogeneity from patient to

604
00:35:17.380 --> 00:35:20.620
patient, but these tumors generally share two common

605
00:35:20.680 --> 00:35:24.670
features. One is activating mutations in KRAS, something you'll no doubt

606
00:35:24.720 --> 00:35:28.640
hear very much about at this meeting, and the second is that

607
00:35:28.680 --> 00:35:32.080
during disease progression, the epithelial compartment

608
00:35:32.160 --> 00:35:35.300
coevolves with this progressively dense

609
00:35:35.420 --> 00:35:39.300
desmoplastic stroma. And the stroma, of course, includes abundant immune

610
00:35:39.420 --> 00:35:43.380
cells and extracellular matrix components and is really set up by a

611
00:35:43.500 --> 00:35:46.320
prominent population of cancer-associated fibroblasts.

612
00:35:47.000 --> 00:35:50.840
So it stands to reason that during this dynamic coevolution of

613
00:35:50.860 --> 00:35:53.900
epithelium and stroma, these fibroblastic

614
00:35:54.340 --> 00:35:58.050
cells may very well have totally different molecular profiles

615
00:35:58.360 --> 00:36:01.680
and functional consequences over time with respect to tumor

616
00:36:01.700 --> 00:36:05.520
progression. So as a field, we've really learned

617
00:36:05.680 --> 00:36:09.120
a great deal about factors or functions that fibroblasts

618
00:36:09.300 --> 00:36:13.120
gain during tumor progression. As a community, we've seen

619
00:36:13.180 --> 00:36:17.160
really nice studies showing that a CAF can produce immune

620
00:36:17.220 --> 00:36:20.980
suppressive cytokines, chemokines, matrix components, and other

621
00:36:21.020 --> 00:36:23.780
factors that can promote tumor genesis.

622
00:36:24.340 --> 00:36:28.280
And in enacting this perturbed wound-healing response in the context of cancer,

623
00:36:28.660 --> 00:36:32.260
they can also engage functions that are tumor restraining, including

624
00:36:32.300 --> 00:36:35.460
engaging Hedgehog signaling, as Stephanie talked about earlier.

625
00:36:35.769 --> 00:36:39.720
And there's also some really nice evidence that collagen I production can have some

626
00:36:39.800 --> 00:36:43.706
tumor-restraining consequences as well.But what

627
00:36:43.796 --> 00:36:47.536
we've really learned less about as a community is factors that are

628
00:36:47.576 --> 00:36:51.436
expressed in normal tissue mesenchyme and that are lost over the

629
00:36:51.496 --> 00:36:52.756
course of tumorigenesis,

630
00:36:53.676 --> 00:36:56.586
which may potentially be barriers to tumor progression.

631
00:36:57.656 --> 00:37:00.996
So really our motivation to think about this comes from

632
00:37:01.036 --> 00:37:04.276
these pioneering studies from the labs of Laura Wood and Marina

633
00:37:04.316 --> 00:37:08.116
Pawlikowska-Magliano that sort of took our collective breath away in

634
00:37:08.156 --> 00:37:12.066
reporting that most adults, including

635
00:37:12.076 --> 00:37:15.756
donors with no evidence of cancer, walk around with

636
00:37:15.896 --> 00:37:19.296
pre-invasive lesions called PANNs in our pancreas.

637
00:37:19.336 --> 00:37:22.856
So just as many of us walk around with BRAF mutant moles on our skin,

638
00:37:23.416 --> 00:37:26.156
many of us walk around with KRAS mutant lesions in our

639
00:37:26.216 --> 00:37:29.256
pancreas. The good news is that these lesions

640
00:37:29.556 --> 00:37:33.406
vastly outnumber cases of invasive pancreatic

641
00:37:33.436 --> 00:37:37.356
cancer. But the frequency of these lesions, this new normal

642
00:37:37.436 --> 00:37:40.956
or newly appreciated normal, really compels us to ask why?

643
00:37:41.576 --> 00:37:45.476
What are the mechanisms active in many of us that are keeping these lesions

644
00:37:45.556 --> 00:37:47.216
from progressing to invasive cancer?

645
00:37:47.686 --> 00:37:51.516
And can we learn from those mechanisms about biomarkers for

646
00:37:51.596 --> 00:37:54.766
those at risk of progression and/or for preventative strategies?

647
00:37:55.676 --> 00:37:59.476
So I think it's very likely that tissue-level tumor suppression

648
00:37:59.516 --> 00:38:03.396
takes three forms. One, of course, is epithelial cell intrinsic mechanisms,

649
00:38:03.436 --> 00:38:06.596
expression and activity of p53 as a key example.

650
00:38:07.336 --> 00:38:10.816
Surely, there are roles of the immune microenvironment in

651
00:38:10.896 --> 00:38:12.856
keeping those lesions from progressing.

652
00:38:13.216 --> 00:38:16.896
But what I'll talk about today are the non-immune microenvironmental

653
00:38:17.196 --> 00:38:20.016
mechanisms that are at play in the pancreas.

654
00:38:20.056 --> 00:38:23.916
And really, these tumor suppression mechanisms likely vary

655
00:38:23.976 --> 00:38:27.726
from individual to individual, and probably some mathematical modeling is needed

656
00:38:28.256 --> 00:38:30.796
to infer temporal dynamics among the three.

657
00:38:31.396 --> 00:38:34.696
So we really wanted to look in the mesenchyme to see if it could teach us about any

658
00:38:35.036 --> 00:38:37.326
new obligate barriers to tumorigenesis.

659
00:38:37.696 --> 00:38:40.586
And this was a project led by a wonderful graduate student in the lab, Catherine

660
00:38:40.636 --> 00:38:43.836
Onyate, together with her lab mates, Chet and Shahini.

661
00:38:45.256 --> 00:38:48.436
So before I get into the data, I just want to talk about what's in the pancreatic

662
00:38:48.516 --> 00:38:52.416
mesenchyme. There's a kind of cell in both the pancreas and the liver called a

663
00:38:52.516 --> 00:38:56.205
stellate cell. These are lipid-storing cells that can sense and

664
00:38:56.276 --> 00:39:00.266
respond to the presence of cancer or a wound-healing insult and

665
00:39:00.316 --> 00:39:02.456
give rise to activated fibroblasts.

666
00:39:02.736 --> 00:39:06.656
It's not the whole story, though, and we know this just based on how we

667
00:39:06.676 --> 00:39:10.536
isolate these cells in the lab. So if you want to isolate stellate cells from

668
00:39:10.716 --> 00:39:14.676
normal, healthy pancreas or liver tissue, you make a single cell suspension,

669
00:39:14.726 --> 00:39:18.316
you run it through a density gradient, and because these stellate cells are such

670
00:39:18.416 --> 00:39:22.096
robust lipid-storing cells, they'll stay trapped at the

671
00:39:22.136 --> 00:39:24.116
interface of this density gradient.

672
00:39:24.776 --> 00:39:28.676
What you see sinking into this dense layer on the bottom is a bunch

673
00:39:28.716 --> 00:39:32.396
of these conventional PDGF or alpha-positive tissue-resident

674
00:39:32.416 --> 00:39:36.256
fibroblasts, which are also sitting in the tissue, also poised to

675
00:39:36.296 --> 00:39:39.916
sense and respond to the presence of cancer and give rise to CAFs.

676
00:39:39.976 --> 00:39:43.216
Just showing you a little bit of evidence that these cells are different.

677
00:39:43.276 --> 00:39:46.976
Right after you plate these stellate cells in culture, you can see the

678
00:39:46.996 --> 00:39:50.145
cytoplasmic lipid droplets, even evident by bright fields.

679
00:39:50.616 --> 00:39:54.416
Within a couple of days, these cells will sort of spontaneously undergo

680
00:39:54.425 --> 00:39:57.356
activation to sort of a myofibroblast-like

681
00:39:57.396 --> 00:40:00.796
morphology. But within those lipid droplets, they store

682
00:40:01.116 --> 00:40:04.696
esterified vitamin As, retinol esters, and they have this characteristic

683
00:40:04.705 --> 00:40:08.536
blue-green autofluorescence that you can even see in your tissue culture microscope

684
00:40:08.596 --> 00:40:11.865
using the DAPI channel. And so, these are different

685
00:40:11.876 --> 00:40:14.356
populations that are poised to give rise to CAFs.

686
00:40:14.566 --> 00:40:18.376
I'm really not going to talk about differences between these populations in normal

687
00:40:18.436 --> 00:40:22.086
tissues or tumors today. But I did just want to make one point,

688
00:40:22.256 --> 00:40:26.166
given that reading abstracts for this meeting, it's just so clear that this

689
00:40:26.256 --> 00:40:29.986
theme has emerged with respect to the importance of spatial niches

690
00:40:30.496 --> 00:40:34.296
in regulating cell function, molecular profiles, and

691
00:40:34.316 --> 00:40:38.216
tumor outcomes. And I think this idea that there are different mesenchymal lineages

692
00:40:38.236 --> 00:40:41.656
that live in our pancreas and give rise to CAFs is really consistent with that.

693
00:40:41.716 --> 00:40:45.136
So specifically, stellate cells in liver and pancreas are in the

694
00:40:45.176 --> 00:40:48.956
perivascular niche, whereas these conventional fibroblasts generally

695
00:40:49.076 --> 00:40:52.856
accumulate in peri-ductal and peri-acinar spaces. Okay.

696
00:40:52.916 --> 00:40:56.796
So in thinking about how to study these, there's a really nice Cre-based mouse

697
00:40:56.876 --> 00:41:00.256
model, the FEBP4 Cre model, that's been used to study

698
00:41:00.276 --> 00:41:03.995
adipocytes in vivo. So needless to say, this is not a stellate cell-specific Cre.

699
00:41:04.516 --> 00:41:08.326
But what's nice is that it robustly induces recombination in sort of

700
00:41:08.376 --> 00:41:11.176
professional fat-storing cells in the body.

701
00:41:11.186 --> 00:41:15.146
And this includes stellate cells in the pancreas and liver, but does not

702
00:41:15.176 --> 00:41:18.936
include conventional fibroblasts. So it's a way to kind of pick apart the two.

703
00:41:18.976 --> 00:41:22.696
This can be combined with lineage tracing tools, in this case, the

704
00:41:22.736 --> 00:41:26.396
Rosa MTMG allele. So we can indelibly label

705
00:41:26.456 --> 00:41:29.436
stellate cells and the CAFs derived from them in green.

706
00:41:29.956 --> 00:41:33.736
And so in this study, we really wanted to understand the temporal dynamics

707
00:41:33.746 --> 00:41:37.376
of mesenchymal activation during pancreatic tumorigenesis and really

708
00:41:37.416 --> 00:41:41.176
understand what gets lost. And in this case, instead of looking at all the

709
00:41:41.236 --> 00:41:44.876
fibroblasts in the pancreas, all the fibroblasts in the tumor, we thought

710
00:41:44.936 --> 00:41:48.176
maybe we'll learn something new if we look at a more focused

711
00:41:48.276 --> 00:41:50.516
population and track it over time.

712
00:41:50.956 --> 00:41:54.826
So we're going to focus on this lipid-storing origin and the CAFs derived from them

713
00:41:54.856 --> 00:41:58.606
in this example. Okay, so what we did is we took this

714
00:41:58.616 --> 00:42:02.496
reporter model. We took stellate cells from a healthy pancreas

715
00:42:02.536 --> 00:42:06.296
tissue, CAFs derived from them from tumors, and did single-cell RNA-seq on

716
00:42:06.336 --> 00:42:10.176
these GFP-positive cells. So just as sort of a sanity check, we

717
00:42:10.216 --> 00:42:14.096
looked at these cells in both normal tissues on the left and tumors

718
00:42:14.156 --> 00:42:18.056
on the right. We see that they sort of express all the classic mesenchymal markers.

719
00:42:18.076 --> 00:42:20.116
They pervasively express vimentin.

720
00:42:20.146 --> 00:42:24.026
They're along this continuum from PI16 positivity

721
00:42:24.056 --> 00:42:27.816
to collagen 15A1 positivity. This is the trajectory

722
00:42:27.876 --> 00:42:31.816
of universal fibroblasts that was reported in the study from Shannon Turley

723
00:42:31.856 --> 00:42:34.126
and Matt Buechler that Stephanie mentioned earlier.

724
00:42:34.796 --> 00:42:38.756
And most of them express one of the universal fibroblast markers, collagen

725
00:42:38.876 --> 00:42:42.496
4A1 or HSPG2 or perlecan. I did

726
00:42:42.696 --> 00:42:45.516
mention that these are in the perivascular niche.

727
00:42:45.996 --> 00:42:48.696
In the liver, stellate cells have been called the pericytes of the liver, though

728
00:42:48.706 --> 00:42:52.296
I'll just mention they seem to lack robust expression of conventional

729
00:42:52.336 --> 00:42:56.288
pericyte markers.Okay, so then what are the differences across

730
00:42:56.328 --> 00:43:00.288
tissue states? So in the context of tumorigenesis, these

731
00:43:00.328 --> 00:43:04.028
cells gain expression of the expected players, immune suppressive

732
00:43:04.038 --> 00:43:07.688
cytokines, CCL2, IL6, and IL33, just as a few

733
00:43:07.728 --> 00:43:11.588
examples. So we looked at what gets lost, and we really wanted to

734
00:43:11.628 --> 00:43:15.508
look at factors with the potential to function in a paracrine manner and

735
00:43:15.568 --> 00:43:17.748
influence other cell states in the tissue.

736
00:43:18.208 --> 00:43:22.168
And a gene that really leapt out from this analysis was a gene called Kit ligand

737
00:43:22.208 --> 00:43:26.068
or stem cell factor, which was clearly expressed in normal pancreas

738
00:43:26.108 --> 00:43:29.408
tissue but really seemed to be lost in tumors.

739
00:43:29.448 --> 00:43:33.268
And this is consistent with a pseudotime analysis that we performed on these

740
00:43:33.288 --> 00:43:35.788
cells. Okay, so what is Kit ligand?

741
00:43:35.828 --> 00:43:39.717
Generally, Kit ligand is a paracrine factor that is

742
00:43:39.768 --> 00:43:42.588
expressed by so-called sender cells in either a

743
00:43:42.688 --> 00:43:45.188
membrane-associated or a secreted form.

744
00:43:45.518 --> 00:43:49.488
It signals through a receptor c-Kit on the surface

745
00:43:49.548 --> 00:43:52.948
of receiver cells and generally is thought to

746
00:43:53.028 --> 00:43:56.888
activate mitogenic processes and pathways, Ras MAP kinase

747
00:43:56.928 --> 00:44:00.048
signaling, Jak-Stat, and PI3 kinase/AKT signaling.

748
00:44:01.148 --> 00:44:04.588
There is certainly a precedent for thinking about Kit ligand in the

749
00:44:04.648 --> 00:44:08.508
context of the mesenchyme. For example, there was a really nice study some time

750
00:44:08.568 --> 00:44:08.928
ago

751
00:44:09.728 --> 00:44:13.628
showing that there are leptin receptor-positive mesenchymal

752
00:44:13.688 --> 00:44:17.448
cells that indeed express Kit ligand, and these are specifically

753
00:44:17.488 --> 00:44:20.098
hepatic stellate cells in the fetal liver.

754
00:44:20.398 --> 00:44:24.198
And this Kit ligand expression by hepatic stellate cells is actually critical for

755
00:44:24.208 --> 00:44:27.668
normal hematopoiesis in the fetal liver at the appropriate

756
00:44:27.988 --> 00:44:31.488
stage of embryogenesis. Now, this idea that leptin

757
00:44:31.528 --> 00:44:35.468
receptor-positive mesenchyme expresses Kit ligand is something that's been

758
00:44:35.508 --> 00:44:39.188
reported in other anatomic contexts, including the bone marrow stroma.

759
00:44:39.608 --> 00:44:43.488
So we asked, okay, are we looking at actually a leptin receptor-positive

760
00:44:43.588 --> 00:44:47.148
component of the pancreas? And so what we did

761
00:44:47.468 --> 00:44:51.188
is we looked at quiescent stellate cells taken fresh from mouse

762
00:44:51.208 --> 00:44:54.268
pancreas, saw that these actually express really high levels of the leptin

763
00:44:54.308 --> 00:44:58.148
receptor. But when these cells are just spontaneously activated to a fibroblastic

764
00:44:58.208 --> 00:45:01.248
state in culture, they lose the expression of this leptin receptor,

765
00:45:01.847 --> 00:45:05.608
suggesting that indeed, this is part of this kind of anatomically conserved

766
00:45:05.648 --> 00:45:09.488
population of leptin receptor-positive mesenchymal cells that for some

767
00:45:09.548 --> 00:45:13.448
reason express Kit ligand. Okay. So we were motivated to ask

768
00:45:13.488 --> 00:45:17.308
what is the functional significance of this factor in normal pancreas

769
00:45:17.368 --> 00:45:21.208
tissue? But first, we really wanted to validate that it was expressed in mice

770
00:45:21.268 --> 00:45:24.868
but also in human pancreas. So we did a number of

771
00:45:24.888 --> 00:45:27.268
experiments doing RNA in situ hybridization.

772
00:45:27.348 --> 00:45:31.108
Kit ligands, like a number of other secreted factors, just cannot be reliably

773
00:45:31.148 --> 00:45:34.938
detected by conventional immunohistochemistry using commercially available

774
00:45:35.048 --> 00:45:35.648
antibodies.

775
00:45:36.588 --> 00:45:40.357
So we did a series of RNA fish experiments showing indeed that

776
00:45:40.428 --> 00:45:44.248
the mesenchymal component of mouse pancreas expresses

777
00:45:44.308 --> 00:45:48.208
Kit ligand. And importantly, we used floxed alleles, this is a model

778
00:45:48.228 --> 00:45:51.288
I'll get back to later, to show that our RNA fish

779
00:45:52.368 --> 00:45:53.938
experimental approach was specific.

780
00:45:54.548 --> 00:45:57.588
So we then went on to look at human pancreas tissues.

781
00:45:57.828 --> 00:46:01.608
We costained for vimentin to mark mesenchyme and Kit ligand, and we

782
00:46:01.628 --> 00:46:04.968
indeed saw expression of Kit ligand in human pancreas tissue.

783
00:46:05.288 --> 00:46:08.728
And importantly, though there is, of course, an exuberant mesenchymal

784
00:46:08.748 --> 00:46:12.548
population in human pancreatic cancer, we saw a significant

785
00:46:12.588 --> 00:46:16.528
reduction of Kit ligand-positive mesenchyme in invasive

786
00:46:16.588 --> 00:46:19.488
cancer. And this was, of course, conserved in mice.

787
00:46:20.148 --> 00:46:24.058
Okay, so we wanted to really confirm this further in the human pancreas, but also

788
00:46:24.128 --> 00:46:27.908
really assess the relevance of this mesenchymal population we were

789
00:46:27.948 --> 00:46:31.768
studying in mice. And so we leveraged a protocol we're employing where we're

790
00:46:31.848 --> 00:46:35.488
taking pieces of benign pancreas tissue from humans.

791
00:46:35.528 --> 00:46:39.448
These are people who come into Memorial Hospital for resection of a primary

792
00:46:39.488 --> 00:46:42.388
tumor, so I can't call this normal pancreas tissue.

793
00:46:42.428 --> 00:46:45.888
This is benign adjacent. That's a meaningful caveat there.

794
00:46:46.168 --> 00:46:49.708
But we've worked out a pipeline similar to what we do in mice, where we can take

795
00:46:49.768 --> 00:46:53.448
this benign pancreas tissue, subject it to density centrifugation.

796
00:46:53.688 --> 00:46:57.408
We can isolate fibroblasts. We can isolate stellate cells and study those on their

797
00:46:57.468 --> 00:47:01.158
own, or either co-culture them with organoids or

798
00:47:01.288 --> 00:47:05.148
culture them on collagen-coated plates together with cancer cell-derived secreted

799
00:47:05.248 --> 00:47:08.648
factors in the form of conditioned media to make CAFs from them.

800
00:47:09.168 --> 00:47:12.868
And so we see that the stellate cells look like stellate cells, kind of similar to

801
00:47:12.888 --> 00:47:16.428
what we see in mice with these abundant cytoplasmic lipid droplets.

802
00:47:16.488 --> 00:47:19.108
We see this in every patient that we've analyzed so far.

803
00:47:19.588 --> 00:47:23.508
And when you culture them, both the stellate cells and the fibroblasts very readily

804
00:47:23.568 --> 00:47:27.108
give rise to really what looks like a conventional myofibroblast or a

805
00:47:27.188 --> 00:47:31.180
CAF.And so we looked in these cells to see if they express Kit ligand, and the

806
00:47:31.200 --> 00:47:32.320
good news is that they do.

807
00:47:33.280 --> 00:47:37.200
When we take these fresh out of human pancreas tissue, they express this marker.

808
00:47:37.520 --> 00:47:41.460
But when we activate them, either with conditioned media or just with recombinant

809
00:47:41.520 --> 00:47:44.720
TGF-beta, we see a significant reduction of this factor.

810
00:47:44.840 --> 00:47:48.720
So it seemed like this was a thing. So we then wanted to ask, okay,

811
00:47:48.760 --> 00:47:51.820
we've looked in normal, we've looked in cancer.

812
00:47:51.840 --> 00:47:55.410
What happens in between? And so we wanted to look in the context of

813
00:47:55.440 --> 00:47:59.140
pannens. And so we went back into our mouse models, and we used a dual

814
00:47:59.160 --> 00:48:02.900
recombinase genetically engineered mouse model that allows us for

815
00:48:02.980 --> 00:48:06.720
fate mapping of stromal evolution in the context of stepwise

816
00:48:06.780 --> 00:48:10.200
tumorigenesis. So this is something that's missed when we do orthotopic

817
00:48:10.240 --> 00:48:13.060
transplantation of invasive cancer cells.

818
00:48:13.080 --> 00:48:16.910
But these genetically engineered mouse models go through these pre-invasive

819
00:48:16.910 --> 00:48:20.830
stages that many of us harbor. And so when we looked in

820
00:48:20.880 --> 00:48:24.669
pannen lesions from pancreas tissue, we saw that

821
00:48:24.700 --> 00:48:28.660
really this GFP positive mesenchymal seems to be sort of at

822
00:48:28.720 --> 00:48:32.480
a steady state of abundance in pre-invasive lesions versus

823
00:48:32.599 --> 00:48:36.180
tumors. And when we looked at Kit ligand, we saw really

824
00:48:36.440 --> 00:48:38.930
negligible signal in regions of invasive cancer.

825
00:48:39.260 --> 00:48:42.820
But we saw some retention in the GFP positive stroma in the

826
00:48:42.880 --> 00:48:45.120
context of these pre-invasive lesions.

827
00:48:45.160 --> 00:48:47.540
And this is something we really want to look into further.

828
00:48:48.030 --> 00:48:51.880
The last piece before we went forward with functional studies was, is its

829
00:48:51.940 --> 00:48:53.920
partner there? Does it have someone to talk to?

830
00:48:54.260 --> 00:48:58.100
And so we looked at expression of c-Kit in normal pancreas tissue, and

831
00:48:58.120 --> 00:49:01.780
we did see expression of both c-Kit itself, as well as the activated

832
00:49:01.900 --> 00:49:05.500
phosphorylated form, in both human and mouse

833
00:49:05.580 --> 00:49:09.280
pancreas. I will mention that the c-Kit and Kit ligand,

834
00:49:09.820 --> 00:49:13.700
it's rare, and it's in these defined niches where both the receptor

835
00:49:13.710 --> 00:49:15.480
and the ligand are in the same region.

836
00:49:15.520 --> 00:49:17.810
That's something we can maybe talk about during Q&amp;A.

837
00:49:18.310 --> 00:49:20.560
And so together we thought, all right, this is a thing.

838
00:49:20.600 --> 00:49:22.979
This is active in normal pancreas. What does it do?

839
00:49:23.010 --> 00:49:26.870
And so we addressed that by doing transcriptional profiling and loss and

840
00:49:26.960 --> 00:49:30.760
gain-of-function systems, and also perturbing Kit ligand in conditions of

841
00:49:30.800 --> 00:49:33.360
health, injury, and cancer in vivo.

842
00:49:33.600 --> 00:49:37.180
So first, to do transcriptional profiling, we used stellate cells in

843
00:49:37.240 --> 00:49:41.129
culture. They really give rise to CAFs nicely when

844
00:49:41.180 --> 00:49:44.620
you culture them. But the approximation of stellate cells in culture really is

845
00:49:44.660 --> 00:49:47.960
something in between what's normal and what's a CAF.

846
00:49:48.040 --> 00:49:51.900
Because in culture, of course, they're not really exposed to the rich milieu of

847
00:49:51.960 --> 00:49:53.840
factors that's in an intact tumor.

848
00:49:54.280 --> 00:49:57.760
And so we reasoned that probably to really understand what Kit ligand is doing

849
00:49:57.820 --> 00:50:01.740
here, we should do both gain and loss of function experiments to knock

850
00:50:01.840 --> 00:50:05.760
down Kit ligand to where it is in a tumor and to overexpress it to where

851
00:50:05.780 --> 00:50:09.360
it is in normal pancreas. And so we did both and did molecular

852
00:50:09.460 --> 00:50:12.740
profiling by RNA-seq to understand what Kit ligand does.

853
00:50:13.200 --> 00:50:17.060
I'll just briefly mention that subpopulations of these cells express c-Kit, so the

854
00:50:17.380 --> 00:50:19.780
Kit ligand had someone to talk to in these cultures.

855
00:50:20.400 --> 00:50:24.300
And so what we found is that Kit ligand seems to positively regulate

856
00:50:24.360 --> 00:50:28.110
a network of genes that we would predict is associated with

857
00:50:28.160 --> 00:50:30.330
maintenance of normal tissue architecture.

858
00:50:30.420 --> 00:50:34.409
So this includes a number of components of basement membrane and

859
00:50:34.460 --> 00:50:38.020
matrix components, really, that are associated with keeping our tissues intact.

860
00:50:38.520 --> 00:50:42.230
But we also saw negative regulation of factors that are

861
00:50:42.260 --> 00:50:45.400
involved really in detrimental CAF functions, including

862
00:50:45.600 --> 00:50:49.440
LRRC15. This was a marker described by Shannon Turley's lab

863
00:50:50.340 --> 00:50:54.180
that may or may not be functional itself, but marks a CAF state really

864
00:50:54.220 --> 00:50:57.650
associated with immune suppression and resistance to immunotherapy.

865
00:50:58.160 --> 00:51:01.940
It also negatively regulated expression of a number of immune suppressive cytokine

866
00:51:01.960 --> 00:51:05.420
and chemokine genes. And generally speaking, our loss and gain-of-function

867
00:51:05.480 --> 00:51:07.180
experiments agreed with one another.

868
00:51:07.820 --> 00:51:11.439
So from here, we moved into functional studies. We started in just healthy mice.

869
00:51:11.800 --> 00:51:15.100
We conditionally deleted Kit ligand in the pancreatic mesenchymal.

870
00:51:15.440 --> 00:51:19.060
We did H&amp;E, saw no differences. But we were

871
00:51:19.120 --> 00:51:21.960
undeterred, so we crossed in a reporter.

872
00:51:22.560 --> 00:51:25.800
Of course, still no difference by H&amp;E, but really thought to take a look under the

873
00:51:25.860 --> 00:51:29.770
hood, and we did some multiplexed imaging analysis using

874
00:51:29.860 --> 00:51:32.770
CODEX in collaboration with Sung Kim's lab at Stanford.

875
00:51:33.300 --> 00:51:36.540
And so really, there were two differences that caught our eye and motivated us to

876
00:51:36.580 --> 00:51:40.560
keep going. The first is that when we conditionally deleted Kit ligand,

877
00:51:40.880 --> 00:51:44.840
we saw this significant increase in CD45 positive cells or

878
00:51:44.880 --> 00:51:47.900
leukocytes that were recruited into pancreas tissue.

879
00:51:47.909 --> 00:51:51.620
And the second, which we think is related, is an increase in the abundance of

880
00:51:51.680 --> 00:51:54.920
perivascular mesenchymal, or these cells that are touching

881
00:51:55.200 --> 00:51:58.860
endothelial cells. And these cells in those positions really are spatially

882
00:51:59.000 --> 00:52:02.620
poised to secrete factors into the bloodstream that promote leukocyte

883
00:52:02.660 --> 00:52:06.460
trafficking or that impact endothelial cells to regulate leukocyte

884
00:52:06.500 --> 00:52:09.720
trafficking themselves. So from here, we moved into an

885
00:52:09.760 --> 00:52:13.480
inflammatory setting, and we engaged a protocol that's been used

886
00:52:13.540 --> 00:52:16.890
heavily by our colleagues in the field using this secretagogue called

887
00:52:16.960 --> 00:52:20.650
cerulean that induces damage of the acinar compartment

888
00:52:20.980 --> 00:52:24.880
and pancreatic inflammation. And in wild-type healthy mice, you

889
00:52:24.900 --> 00:52:28.810
can treat with cerulean. You get an inflammatory reaction in the pancreas, and

890
00:52:28.840 --> 00:52:31.330
that inflammation resolves within a few days.

891
00:52:31.380 --> 00:52:35.160
This has been really nicely benchmarked by many of our colleagues in the field.

892
00:52:35.640 --> 00:52:39.580
I will mention, though, that a combination of cerulean and a

893
00:52:39.640 --> 00:52:42.460
K-RAS mutation gives something very different.

894
00:52:42.480 --> 00:52:46.460
In that case, the inflammation does not get resolved and actually really

895
00:52:46.980 --> 00:52:50.940
drives the formation of pre-invasive lesions in mouse pancreas.

896
00:52:51.510 --> 00:52:55.260
And so what we found, really to our surprise, is that when we induced

897
00:52:55.270 --> 00:52:58.720
pancreatic inflammation in the absence of Kit ligand, we saw really much more

898
00:52:58.760 --> 00:53:02.500
inflammation, as well as a clear increase in what looked

899
00:53:02.540 --> 00:53:06.080
like an acinar-to-ductal metaplasia within the

900
00:53:06.120 --> 00:53:10.040
pancreatic epithelium. And this really aligned with what people have reported in

901
00:53:10.060 --> 00:53:13.880
the context of a K-RAS mutation in the pancreatic epithelial compartment,

902
00:53:14.260 --> 00:53:17.460
motivating us to ask whether there's some sort of paracrine

903
00:53:17.880 --> 00:53:21.530
inverse relationship between Kit ligand in the stroma and

904
00:53:21.600 --> 00:53:25.516
K-RAS signaling in the epithelium.And so we wanted to look a

905
00:53:25.556 --> 00:53:29.336
little bit more carefully at this idea that kit ligand negatively

906
00:53:29.356 --> 00:53:31.436
regulates epithelial plasticity.

907
00:53:31.476 --> 00:53:35.436
This acinar to ductal metaplasia is an early step of pancreatic

908
00:53:35.446 --> 00:53:39.406
tumorigenesis. And so you can see that in our control mice,

909
00:53:39.736 --> 00:53:43.316
you see that most of these acinar cells express amylase.

910
00:53:43.396 --> 00:53:45.266
The ductal cells express pan cytokeratin.

911
00:53:45.576 --> 00:53:47.636
Generally, these are in different cellular compartments.

912
00:53:47.656 --> 00:53:51.216
But when we conditionally knocked out kit ligand, we really saw fairly

913
00:53:51.256 --> 00:53:54.626
extensive co-expression of these markers consistent with

914
00:53:54.696 --> 00:53:57.956
this metaplastic state that's an early stage of

915
00:53:58.016 --> 00:54:01.636
tumorigenesis. And when we looked at the immune composition of these

916
00:54:01.676 --> 00:54:05.126
tissues, we saw a significant increase in CD45 positive

917
00:54:05.216 --> 00:54:08.946
cells and CD68 positive myeloid cells when we had

918
00:54:08.996 --> 00:54:10.926
this conditional kit ligand deletion.

919
00:54:11.526 --> 00:54:13.816
And finally, we looked in the context of cancer.

920
00:54:14.145 --> 00:54:17.976
And what we've now seen in three different implantable models is that when you lose

921
00:54:17.996 --> 00:54:20.976
kit ligand in the stroma, you significantly increase

922
00:54:21.036 --> 00:54:24.576
tumorigenesis. And we're totally

923
00:54:24.656 --> 00:54:28.296
aware of the limitations of the implantable models, but the one point I want to

924
00:54:28.356 --> 00:54:31.976
make here is that in these cases, these are insta-tumor, right?

925
00:54:32.076 --> 00:54:34.916
They've already lost P53. They are invasive cancer.

926
00:54:35.276 --> 00:54:39.076
But even in this case, kit ligand has some sort of tumor restraining

927
00:54:39.116 --> 00:54:42.976
impact at the tissue level, something we certainly want to look into further.

928
00:54:43.576 --> 00:54:47.416
And so to conclude, I hope I've convinced you that normal pancreatic cancer is

929
00:54:47.456 --> 00:54:51.296
not the barrier, but a barrier to tumorigenesis.

930
00:54:51.576 --> 00:54:55.236
We nominate stromal kit ligand as one factor that seems to limit

931
00:54:55.656 --> 00:54:58.156
epithelial plasticity and inflammation.

932
00:54:58.816 --> 00:55:02.736
The real relevance for epithelial sulfate is something we've only just started to

933
00:55:02.776 --> 00:55:06.596
look into and think about. In human pancreas tissue, we really need to

934
00:55:06.636 --> 00:55:10.476
dig deeper and understand where and when kit ligand gets lost

935
00:55:10.536 --> 00:55:13.866
during tumorigenesis. And of course, we want to really better

936
00:55:14.196 --> 00:55:17.756
understand what's happening in this dual recombinase genetic mouse model to

937
00:55:17.776 --> 00:55:20.436
understand what happens to PanIN progression in these mice.

938
00:55:20.896 --> 00:55:24.676
And the ultimate goal really is to think about downstream mediators that may serve

939
00:55:24.736 --> 00:55:27.746
as targets for interception or as biomarkers of progression.

940
00:55:28.276 --> 00:55:31.336
And so with that, I'll conclude. I'll thank all the wonderful people in my lab,

941
00:55:31.376 --> 00:55:33.216
especially Kathrina, who did this work.

942
00:55:33.576 --> 00:55:35.976
Thanks to our wonderful collaborators and funding sources.

943
00:55:36.016 --> 00:55:39.416
And with that, I'll thank you all for your attention and gladly take any questions.

944
00:55:48.536 --> 00:55:52.436
Very nice talk. And you mentioned there's a key

945
00:55:52.896 --> 00:55:56.036
role of the kit ligand during the

946
00:55:56.396 --> 00:55:58.396
pancreatic cancer progression, right?

947
00:55:58.776 --> 00:56:02.216
So I'm curious about the loss of the kit

948
00:56:02.476 --> 00:56:06.376
ligand expression in CAF. Is it a consequence or trigger of

949
00:56:06.496 --> 00:56:08.976
the poor cancer progression? Thank you.

950
00:56:09.036 --> 00:56:12.796
Yeah, no, it's a great question. So I sort of glossed over it, but

951
00:56:13.336 --> 00:56:16.716
TGF-beta alone was sufficient in our, at least,

952
00:56:16.856 --> 00:56:20.356
experimental culture models to induce loss of kit

953
00:56:20.396 --> 00:56:24.336
ligand from the mesenchyme. So TGF-beta gets induced in the

954
00:56:24.416 --> 00:56:27.516
pancreatic epithelium pretty early in tumorigenesis.

955
00:56:27.526 --> 00:56:31.456
So I think a possibility is that kit ligand sticks around kind

956
00:56:31.496 --> 00:56:35.196
of in the early stages of tumorigenesis, but once there's enough TGF-beta,

957
00:56:35.756 --> 00:56:39.736
then kit ligand gets downregulated, and it's presumably part of a

958
00:56:39.796 --> 00:56:42.936
program that serves as a barrier to tumorigenesis.

959
00:56:44.136 --> 00:56:47.776
I think probably there are other signals in an

960
00:56:47.816 --> 00:56:51.196
intact tumor. We did the is TGF-beta sufficient.

961
00:56:51.236 --> 00:56:54.786
We haven't knocked out TGF-beta in the context of conditioned media, for example,

962
00:56:54.836 --> 00:56:58.796
to ask whether it's necessary with all those other signals around.

963
00:56:58.816 --> 00:57:02.796
But certainly, that's a key factor that we think probably mechanistically is

964
00:57:02.836 --> 00:57:05.016
related to kit ligand regulation and expression.

965
00:57:05.276 --> 00:57:05.966
